.ds n) explain_getpgrp
.cp 0  \" Solaris defaults to ''.cp 1'', sheesh.
.TH explain_getpgrp 3
.SH NAME
explain_getpgrp \- explain \f[I]getpgrp\fP(2) errors
.if require_index \{
.XX "explain_getpgrp(3)" "explain \f[I]getpgrp\fP(2) errors"
.\}
.SH SYNOPSIS
#include <libexplain/getpgrp.h>
.sp 0.3
.ad l
const char *explain_getpgrp(pid_t pid);
.br
const char *explain_errno_getpgrp(int errnum, pid_t pid);
.br
void explain_message_getpgrp(char *message, int message_size, pid_t pid);
.br
void explain_message_errno_getpgrp(char *message, int message_size, int
errnum, pid_t pid);
.ad b
.SH DESCRIPTION
These functions may be used to obtain explanations for errors returned by
the \f[I]getpgrp\fP(2) system call.
.PP
\f[B]Note:\fP the \f[I]getpgrp\fP(2) function has two implementations.
The POSIX.1 version has no arguments, while the BSD version has one
argument.  For simplicity of implementation, the argument list seen here
includes the \f[I]pid\fP argument.
.PP
The POSIX.1 \f[CW]getpgid()\fP semantics can be obtained by calling
\f[CW]getpgrp(0)\fP on BSD systems, and this is the API for
libexplain, even on systems that do not use the BSD API.
.\" ----------------------------------------------------
.SS explain_getpgrp
.ad l
const char *explain_getpgrp(pid_t pid);
.ad b
.PP
The \f[B]explain_getpgrp\fP function is used to obtain an explanation of an
error returned by the \f[I]getpgrp\fP(2) system call. The least the message
will contain is the value of \f[CW]strerror(errno)\fP, but usually it will
do much better, and indicate the underlying cause in more detail.
.PP
The \f[I]errno\fP global variable will be used to obtain the error value to
be decoded.
.TP 8n
\f[I]pid\fP
The original pid, exactly as passed to the \f[I]getpgrp\fP(2) system call.
.TP 8n
Returns:
The message explaining the error. This message buffer is shared by all
libexplain functions which do not supply a buffer in their argument list.
This will be overwritten by the next call to any libexplain function which
shares this buffer, including other threads.
.PP
\f[B]Note:\fP This function is \f[B]not\fP thread safe, because it shares a
return buffer across all threads, and many other functions in this library.
.PP
\f[B]Example:\fP This function is intended to be used in a fashion similar
to the following example:
.RS
.ft CW
.fi
.ad l
pid_t result = getpgrp(pid);
.br
if (result < 0)
.ad b
.nf
{
.fi
.ad l
.in +4n
fprintf(stderr, "%s\en", explain_getpgrp(pid));
.in -4n
.nf
    exit(EXIT_FAILURE);
}
.fi
.ft R
.ad b
.RE
.PP
The above code example is available pre\-packaged as the
\f[I]explain_getpgrp_or_die\fP(3) function.
.\" ----------------------------------------------------
.SS explain_errno_getpgrp
.ad l
const char *explain_errno_getpgrp(int errnum, pid_t pid);
.ad b
.PP
The \f[B]explain_errno_getpgrp\fP function is used to obtain an explanation
of an error returned by the \f[I]getpgrp\fP(2) system call. The least the
message will contain is the value of \f[CW]strerror(errno)\fP, but usually
it will do much better, and indicate the underlying cause in more detail.
.TP 8n
\f[I]errnum\fP
The error value to be decoded, usually obtained from the \f[I]errno\fP
global variable just before this function is called. This is necessary if
you need to call \f[B]any\fP code between the system call to be explained
and this function, because many libc functions will alter the value of
\f[I]errno\fP.
.TP 8n
\f[I]pid\fP
The original pid, exactly as passed to the \f[I]getpgrp\fP(2) system call.
.TP 8n
Returns:
The message explaining the error. This message buffer is shared by all
libexplain functions which do not supply a buffer in their argument list.
This will be overwritten by the next call to any libexplain function which
shares this buffer, including other threads.
.PP
\f[B]Note:\fP This function is \f[B]not\fP thread safe, because it shares a
return buffer across all threads, and many other functions in this library.
.PP
\f[B]Example:\fP This function is intended to be used in a fashion similar
to the following example:
.RS
.ft CW
.fi
.ad l
pid_t result = getpgrp(pid);
.br
if (result < 0)
.ad b
.nf
{
    int err = errno;
.fi
.ad l
.in +4n
fprintf(stderr, "%s\en", explain_errno_getpgrp(err, pid));
.in -4n
.nf
    exit(EXIT_FAILURE);
}
.fi
.ft R
.ad b
.RE
.PP
The above code example is available pre\-packaged as the
\f[I]explain_getpgrp_or_die\fP(3) function.
.\" ----------------------------------------------------
